{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01YPPrrB78vrmwrTjE45Qgpf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the LEVEL-DEFS and KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1: The traveling-salesman heuristic produces a route that is no more than 1.5x the length of the optimal route for inputs up to 20 stops.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about the quality of the TSP heuristic algorithm itself. It's a local algorithmic computation - no external dependencies needed.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS, network, or subprocess needed. Just the algorithm.\n- MOCK-HIDE: No mocking needed - the heuristic is deterministic.\n\n\n- LLM-DEP: No AI/ML involved.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nThe heuristic is a local algorithm that I can test with known coordinates as input, and any failure would be purely algorithmic. This is Unit level.\n\n**Behavior 2: The delivery time window estimates are computed correctly from the distance between consecutive stops and the configured average speed for the road type.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about the computation logic - distance + speed → time window. This is a local calculation.\n- REAL-INFRA: No external dependencies needed.\n- MOCK-HIDE: No mocking needed.\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nThis is pure calculation logic. Unit level.\n\n**Behavior 3: The shift-hours validator rejects a route whose total estimated time exceeds the driver's remaining shift hours, returning the excess amount.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: Validation logic - pure computation.\n- REAL-INFRA: No.\n- MOCK-HIDE: No.\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nPure validation logic. Unit level.\n\n**Behavior 4: When one address in the list fails geocoding (API returns no results), the service skips that stop and optimizes the remaining addresses, reporting which addresses were skipped.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This involves the geocoding API returning no results, then the service coordinating: skip the stop, optimize the remaining, and report which ones failed.\n- REAL-INFRA: The failure mode is about how the service handles a \"no results\" API response and coordinates with the optimizer. A stubbed geocoding client can reproduce this without real HTTP.\n- MOCK-HIDE: A stub API can test whether the service properly skips and reports the failed addresses.\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nThis spans multiple modules (geocoding, optimizer, reporter), so it's integration level. The real failure mode is about module coordination, not actual HTTP behavior.\n\nNow looking at the deduplication behavior - this is about consolidating duplicate addresses into a single stop with combined delivery items. It could be a pure data processing step or involve the geocoding layer. This looks like unit level since it's checking the deduplication and consolidation logic on the input data model.\n\nBut I need to think about whether verifying the stop isn't visited twice in the optimized route requires the full pipeline. If deduplication happens at input validation, I can test it as a unit. If I need to verify the route doesn't visit the consolidated stop twice, that requires integration testing through geocoding and optimization.\n\nI'm settling on Integration for behavior 4 because the failure mode involves multiple modules interacting—the geocoding client, optimizer, and reporter all need to work together. Even though I can stub the API, the control flow across these components is what matters.\n\nSo my final breakdown: behavior 1 is a pure algorithm test, behavior 2 is pure calculation, behavior 3 is pure validation, and behavior 4 requires integration testing across the geocoding and optimization modules.\n\nFor behavior 5, I need to verify the deduplication actually prevents duplicate stops in the final route, which means testing the dedup output flowing through to the optimizer—that's integration-level verification.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out the test descriptions with justifications for each behavior.\n\nFor behavior 1, I'll use a small fixed set of stops with known coordinates, run the TSP heuristic, compute the actual route length against the optimal (which I can brute-force for small inputs), and assert the result stays within 1.5× optimal.\n\nBehavior 2 is straightforward—provide a known distance and configured speed, then verify the time estimate matches expectations.\n\nBehavior 3 checks that the validator correctly identifies when a route exceeds shift hours and reports the overage.\n\nBehavior 4 requires wiring the geocoding client, optimizer, and reporter together with a stubbed geocoding service that returns no results for one address, then confirming the route skips that stop and the report flags it.\n\nBehavior 5 wires the deduplication logic with the optimizer, submitting duplicate addresses with different items, and verifying the optimizer gets a single consolidated stop that appears once in the route.\n\nNow I'm moving on to assign the level_probabilities for each test.\n\nFor behavior 1, the TSP heuristic is a pure algorithm test, so unit dominates at 0.85, with minimal integration and system coverage.\n\nBehavior 2 is also primarily unit-level—just distance and speed math—so 0.92 unit, small integration slice.\n\nBehavior 3 follows the same pattern: mostly unit validation logic with 0.92 unit weight.\n\nBehavior 4 is different—it's fundamentally an integration test since it requires multiple components working together, so integration gets 0.80 while unit drops to 0.05.\n\nBehavior 5 also leans integration at 0.62 since deduplication and optimizer coordination is the core concern, though unit coverage of the dedup logic itself is still meaningful at 0.30.\n\nLet me reconsider behavior 4 more carefully—the geocoding failure is really about how the system handles a missing dependency, which could push system-level testing higher.\n\nActually, no—a stub HTTP client can simulate the failure mode just fine, so integration is the right fit.\n\nFor behavior 5, I'm treating deduplication as a separate module that feeds into the optimizer, which makes this integration-focused.\n\nNow checking the test descriptions against these levels: the TSP test uses fixed coordinates and brute-force comparison, which is pure unit; time window is just distance-speed math, also unit; shift validator totals up time constraints, still unit.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9582,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9582},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4f68bc65-8f95-41df-a482-4bdc672769f2","uuid":"4255846f-9d6a-449c-9c88-d900d000e8c8"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01YPPrrB78vrmwrTjE45Qgpf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01GQtqaYVa41Swa3RuMZRmnE","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The TSP heuristic produces a route no more than 1.5x the optimal length for up to 20 stops.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is entirely within the heuristic algorithm — wrong ordering or pruning decisions. No module boundary is crossed. REAL-INFRA: Inputs are coordinates (plain floats); no OS, network, or subprocess involved. MOCK-HIDE: Nothing to mock; the function is deterministic given fixed inputs. LLM-DEP: No AI/ML. MULTI-STEP: No. For small N (≤20), brute-force optimal is computable in-process and provides a concrete upper-bound reference. This is a pure algorithm quality check that lives entirely inside one function boundary.","test_description":"Construct a fixed set of ≤20 stops with known (x, y) coordinates. Run the TSP heuristic to get its route length. Brute-force the true optimal for the same inputs (feasible for N≤12) or use a known lower bound (e.g., MST length). Assert heuristic_length ≤ 1.5 × optimal_length. Parametrize with at least one adversarial case (e.g., clustered stops that tempt nearest-neighbor into a bad path).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Delivery time window estimates are computed correctly from inter-stop distance and the configured average speed for the road type.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure lives inside the time-estimation formula — wrong unit conversion, wrong speed lookup, or wrong arithmetic. This is a single-function computation, not a module handoff. REAL-INFRA: No I/O; speed config is just a dict or enum lookup. MOCK-HIDE: Nothing to mock; all inputs are passed as arguments. LLM-DEP: No. MULTI-STEP: No. The formula `time = distance / speed` with road-type dispatch is fully exercisable in isolation with parametrized cases.","test_description":"Call the time-window estimation function directly with explicit distance values (e.g., 60 km) and each supported road-type speed config (e.g., highway 100 km/h, urban 30 km/h). Assert the returned window matches the expected duration to within floating-point tolerance. Include edge cases: zero distance, minimum non-zero distance, and a distance that produces a fractional hour.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.92,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The shift-hours validator rejects a route whose total estimated time exceeds the driver's remaining shift hours, returning the excess amount.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is wrong arithmetic or missing rejection logic inside the validator function alone. No inter-module coordination is required to expose it. REAL-INFRA: Inputs are plain numbers (total time, shift hours remaining). MOCK-HIDE: Nothing to mock. LLM-DEP: No. MULTI-STEP: No. The validator is a boundary function: total_time > shift_remaining → return (False, total_time - shift_remaining). All failure modes are reachable with direct numeric inputs.","test_description":"Call the validator directly with (a) total time exactly equal to shift hours → expect acceptance with zero excess; (b) total time one minute over → expect rejection with excess = 1 minute; (c) total time well under → expect acceptance. Assert both the rejection boolean and the returned excess value. Verify the excess is the precise difference, not rounded or clamped.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.92,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When one address fails geocoding (API returns no results), the service skips that stop, optimizes remaining addresses, and reports which were skipped.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure only manifests at the boundary between the geocoding client and the orchestration layer: does the service correctly propagate the 'no results' signal, remove the stop from the candidate list before calling the optimizer, and accumulate it in the skipped-address report? A unit test of any single module cannot catch a bug where the orchestrator passes the bad stop to the optimizer anyway, or forgets to populate the report. REAL-INFRA: The geocoding API is external HTTP in production, but the failure mode (handling an empty-results response) is fully reproducible with a stub HTTP client or a fake geocoding adapter — no real network conditions are required. A stub returning `[]` for a specific address is sufficient. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking at the wrong level (e.g., mocking the geocoder inside the optimizer) would hide the orchestration bug. The stub must be at the geocoding-client boundary so the real orchestration code runs. LLM-DEP: No. MULTI-STEP: No chained agentic steps. REJECTION-GATE for System: the behavior does not mention real network conditions, timeouts, or HTTP-level behavior — the failure is about control-flow with a known API response shape, which a stub reproduces exactly.","test_description":"Wire the real orchestration layer with (a) a stub geocoding client configured to return no results for exactly one address and valid coordinates for the rest, and (b) the real optimizer and reporter. Submit a list of N addresses where one is the failing address. Assert: the optimizer receives exactly N-1 coordinate pairs; the returned route does not include the failing address; the skipped-address report contains exactly that address. Test with the failing address at the start, middle, and end of the input list.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate addresses are consolidated into a single stop with combined delivery items and visited only once in the optimized route.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure can occur at two distinct module boundaries: (a) the deduplication/consolidation step produces a wrong output (wrong item count, wrong stop count), or (b) the consolidated stop is handed correctly to the geocoder and optimizer but the optimizer still schedules two visits (e.g., because deduplication produced two identical coordinate entries). A unit test of the deduplication function alone cannot catch failure mode (b). Verifying 'visited only once' requires the deduplicated stop to flow through to the optimizer and appear in the route exactly once. REAL-INFRA: No real geocoding or HTTP needed; stub geocoding returning the same coordinate for both duplicate addresses is sufficient and is the critical case (same address → same coord → optimizer must not double-visit). MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the optimizer would mask whether it actually deduplicated the visit. The real optimizer must run on the consolidated input. LLM-DEP: No. MULTI-STEP: No agentic steps. REJECTION-GATE for System: no real network or OS behavior is required; a stub geocoder reproduces the exact failure scenario.","test_description":"Wire the deduplication module, stub geocoding client (returning the same coordinate for duplicate addresses), and real optimizer together. Submit two entries with identical address strings and different delivery items. Assert: the geocoder is called exactly once for that address; the optimizer receives exactly one stop for that coordinate; the returned route visits that coordinate exactly once; the consolidated stop's delivery items are the union of both input entries. Also test three duplicates to confirm N-to-1 consolidation scales correctly.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9582,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9582},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4f68bc65-8f95-41df-a482-4bdc672769f2","uuid":"0953c19d-ea9f-447f-aef0-0603016f7c2e"}
